05547nam a22007935i 9780231545754DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017058233  a97802315457547 a10.7312/powe184922doi  a(DE-B1597)500123  a(OCoLC)1014002458  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY10aPN4784 .F6 7aLAN0080002bisacsh04a070.4/3322231 aPowers, Matthew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNGOs as Newsmakers :bThe Changing Landscape of International News /cMatthew Powers. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource :b3 charts  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReuters Institute Global Journalism Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tCHAPTER ONE. A New Era of NGO-Driven News? -- tCHAPTER TWO. The Changing Faces of NGO Communication Work -- tCHAPTER THREE. The Partially Opening News Gates -- tCHAPTER FOUR. The Strategic Advocate in the Digital Storm -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Publicity’s Ends -- tCHAPTER SIX. Explaining the Endurance of News Norms -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. The Possibilities and Limitations of NGO Communication -- tMethods Appendix -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs traditional news outlets’ international coverage has waned, several prominent nongovernmental organizations have taken on a growing number of seemingly journalistic functions. Groups such as Amnesty International, Human Rights Watch, and Médecins Sans Frontières send reporters to gather information and provide analysis and assign photographers and videographers to boost the visibility of their work. Digital technologies and social media have increased the potential for NGOs to communicate directly with the public, bypassing traditional gatekeepers. But have these efforts changed and expanded traditional news practices and coverage—and are there consequences to blurring the lines between reporting and advocacy?In NGOs as Newsmakers, Matthew Powers analyzes the growing role NGOs play in shaping—and sometimes directly producing—international news. Drawing on interviews, observations, and content analysis, he charts the dramatic growth in NGO news-making efforts, examines whether these efforts increase the organizations' chances of garnering news coverage, and analyzes the effects of digital technologies on publicity strategies. Although the contemporary media environment offers NGOs greater opportunities to shape the news, Powers finds, it also subjects them to news-media norms. While advocacy groups can and do provide coverage of otherwise ignored places and topics, they are still dependent on traditional media and political elites and influenced by the expectations of donors, officials, journalists, and NGOs themselves. Through an unprecedented glimpse into NGOs’ newsmaking efforts, Powers portrays the possibilities and limits of NGOs as newsmakers amid the transformations of international news, with important implications for the intersections of journalism and advocacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aForeign news. 0aNon-governmental organizationsxInfluence. 0aReporters and reporting. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Journalism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060660708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Library and Information Science 2018 Englishz978311060404708iTitle is part of eBook pac